# HTML and Accessibility Rules

Use semantic HTML first.

Prefer:
- `header`, `main`, `section`, `article`, `aside`, `footer`
- `button` for actions
- `a` for navigation
- `label` connected to form controls
- Proper heading hierarchy: one `h1`, then logical `h2`, `h3`
- Alt text for meaningful images
- Empty alt text for decorative images
- Keyboard-accessible interactions
- Visible focus states
- ARIA only when native HTML is not enough

Avoid:
- Clickable `div`s
- Buttons without accessible labels
- Placeholder-only form labels
- Skipping heading levels for visual size
- Removing outlines without replacing focus styles
- Using ARIA to fix bad HTML when semantic HTML would solve it

Every modal, dropdown, popover, and menu must be keyboard-friendly.
